<DOC><DOCNO> ZF32-124-264 </DOCNO><DOCID>10 916 390</DOCID><JOURNAL>Electronic News  June 24 1991 v37 n1866 p9(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Sellers beware? (US technology being sold to foreign competition)(Government Closeup) (column)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Connelly, Joanne.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The US Committee on Foreign Investment in the United States(CFIUS) is taking a lazy approach to preventing the piece-by-piecesell-off of US technology to foreign competition.andP;  A report fromthe US Department of Commerce indicates that foreign companiesspent $64.4 billion in 1990 alone to buy or create companies inthe US; Japan outdid every other nation for the first time in 1990by spending $20.5 billion.andP;  Some industry analysts note that thetrend is alarming, especially since these foreign companies arefocusing on strategic industries such as semiconductor equipment,computer software and advanced materials.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Government RegulationForeign CompetitionSemiconductor industryTechnology transferUnited States. Committee on Foreign Investment in the UnitedStatesJapanese Competition.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>